---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Learning";
const description = "How I trained my judgment through sustained study and applied practice.";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="section learning-hero" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <h1>Learning</h1>
    <p class="intro-lead">
      This page shows how I train judgment. Across formal study, field work, and applied systems, I focus on improving how decisions get made when information is incomplete and outcomes carry consequence.
    </p>

    <div class="decision-grid" aria-label="Learning paths">
      <a class="decision-card" href="#formal-learning">
        <span>Formal Study</span>
        <p>Structured learning across Oklahoma State, Stanford, Stanford ICME, and MIT.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="decision-card" href="#field-learning">
        <span>Field Studies</span>
        <p>Applied studies drawn from enterprise systems, automation, and civic infrastructure.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="decision-card" href="#proof">
        <span>Applied Work</span>
        <p>How learning becomes judgment, accountability, and system design.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="formal-learning" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Formal Study</h2>
      <p>I return to structured environments when the questions require more precision.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="foundation-grid">
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Oklahoma State University</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">1992–1994</p>
        <p>Early study established the pattern. I was drawn to environments that forced clarity, even before I knew where it would lead.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Rigor of attending and completing work in a structured environment</li>
          <li>Foundations of computer science</li>
          <li>Discovered a love for writing that I didn’t fully pursue until 2025</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Stanford University</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2005</p>
        <p>I enrolled my team at Yahoo! into a course focused on improvisation. The objective wasn’t performance. It was collaboration: learning how to build on each other’s thinking, articulate ideas in motion, and design without shutting down possibility.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Listening to understand instead of listening to respond</li>
          <li>How to lift others up through words without shutting down conversation</li>
          <li>Actively helping others continue a line of thought</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Stanford University (ICME)</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2016</p>
        <p>Coursework through the Institute for Computational and Mathematical Engineering (ICME) marked a deliberate turn toward data and systems. I focused on how decisions get made when information is incomplete, and how reasoning breaks under pressure.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Foundations of data science that shifted my career trajectory</li>
          <li>A deep interest in statistics and probability</li>
          <li>Introduction of Python and SQL into my working toolkit</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Massachusetts Institute of Technology</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2017–today</p>
        <p>Sustained study through MIT programs has focused on design, AI, and decision systems. This work has been self-directed and ongoing, built on repetition rather than milestones.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Design Thinking as an actionable, repeatable practice</li>
          <li>Strengthened leadership across enterprise and startup environments</li>
          <li>Applying analytics and AI to real decision systems where outcomes carry risk</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="field-learning" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Field Studies</h2>
      <p>These studies translate real environments into usable patterns for designing trust, interpretation, and accountability.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="field-study-grid">
      <article class="field-study-card">
        <a href="/learning/field-studies/dremio" aria-label="Read Field Study: Dremio">
          <img src="/images/writing/field-study-dremio.png" alt="Abstract semantic data structures resolving into navigable pathways" loading="lazy" />
          <div class="field-study-content">
            <p class="entry-meta">Enterprise Data Infrastructure</p>
            <h3>Field Study: Dremio</h3>
            <p>How semantic systems, lineage, and cognitive legibility help people trust complex data environments.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
      </article>

      <article class="field-study-card">
        <a href="/learning/field-studies/automation-anywhere" aria-label="Read Field Study: Automation Anywhere">
          <img src="/images/writing/field-study-automation-anywhere.png" alt="Abstract automation workflows intersecting with human oversight and adaptive systems" loading="lazy" />
          <div class="field-study-content">
            <p class="entry-meta">AI-Assisted Automation</p>
            <h3>Field Study: Automation Anywhere</h3>
            <p>How explainability, confidence calibration, and human oversight shape trust in adaptive automation.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
      </article>

      <article class="field-study-card">
        <a href="/learning/field-studies/civic-systems" aria-label="Read Field Study: Civic Systems">
          <img src="/images/writing/field-study-civic-systems.png" alt="Abstract civic infrastructure and human pathways intersecting across a public system" loading="lazy" />
          <div class="field-study-content">
            <p class="entry-meta">Public Systems</p>
            <h3>Field Study: Civic Systems</h3>
            <p>How navigability, dignity, and operational clarity shape trust inside public systems under stress.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="section-heading secondary-heading">
      <h2>Field Work</h2>
      <p>Additional observations from product teams, civic operations, and learning environments.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="field-list">
      <article class="field-entry">
        <p class="entry-meta">Evernote</p>
        <h3>
          <a href="/learning/evernote-research">Palette as Exploration</a>
        </h3>
        <p>For Skitch, we observed preschool children fingerpaint to understand how people explore color before constraint. The work shifted markup palettes from rigid selection toward fluid exploration.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="field-entry">
        <p class="entry-meta">Yahoo!</p>
        <h3>
          <a href="/learning/stanford-improv">Collaboration at Scale</a>
        </h3>
        <p>Through Stanford improv training, we practiced building on each other’s ideas while designing Yahoo! frontdoor experiences at global scale. Even fractional A/B tests reached millions of users.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="field-entry">
        <p class="entry-meta">Santa Clara County Registrar of Voters</p>
        <h3>
          <a href="/learning/civic-systems">Trust Under Pressure</a>
        </h3>
        <p>Inside election operations, I observed how civic systems behave when procedures meet real edge cases. The work clarified how interpretation determines whether participation and trust hold.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="proof" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Applied Work</h2>
      <p>Learning proves itself only when it changes how decisions are designed, challenged, and held accountable.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="proof-list">
      <article class="proof-entry">
        <p class="proof-principle">Separate signal from output</p>
        <p class="proof-application">Applied in systems where outputs must be interpreted under real conditions.</p>
        <div class="supporting-post">
          <span>Supporting post</span>
          <h3>
            <a href="/writing/when-ai-is-wrong-a-simple-operating-model-for-real-world-systems">
              When AI Is Wrong: A Simple Operating Model for Real-World Systems
            </a>
          </h3>
          <p>A practical operating model for separating signal, interpretation, escalation, and response when AI systems produce outputs that require human judgment.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="proof-entry">
        <p class="proof-principle">Design for human interpretation</p>
        <p class="proof-application">Applied where human judgment is designed into systems with ambiguity, escalation, and accountability.</p>
        <div class="supporting-post">
          <span>Supporting post</span>
          <h3>
            <a href="/writing/designing-dignity">Designing Dignity</a>
          </h3>
          <p>A civic systems argument for rebuilding public infrastructure around human agency, interpretation, and dignity under real-world constraints.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="proof-entry">
        <p class="proof-principle">Design systems that stay accountable when wrong</p>
        <p class="proof-application">Applied in systems that must remain legible, correctable, and trustworthy under pressure.</p>
        <div class="supporting-post">
          <span>Supporting post</span>
          <h3>
            <a href="/writing/the-lineage-of-signal">The Lineage of Signal</a>
          </h3>
          <p>A reflection on the disciplines that make systems legible, durable, and accountable when interpretation carries consequence.</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section learning-close" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>What This Adds Up To</h2>
      <p>Learning only matters if it improves how decisions hold under real conditions.</p>
    </div>
    <p>
      Learning is not accumulation. It’s calibration. It’s how I train for decisions that don’t have clean answers.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every environment above, classroom, product, or civic system, forced the same adjustment: less assumption, more observation, and systems that stay accountable when they’re wrong.
    </p>
    <p>
      I see that same pattern every day in how my son learns—curiosity without hesitation, questions without constraint. It’s also why I’m intentional about where I am and who I’m around.
    </p>
    <p>
      I want decisions that hold up when it actually matters. That’s what I’m learning to do.
    </p>
  </section>

<style>

  .intro-lead {
    max-width: 42rem;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.58;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .decision-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 14px;
    margin-top: 34px;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .decision-card {
    display: block;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 18px;
    text-decoration: none;
    color: inherit;
    transition: border-color 0.2s ease, transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .decision-card:hover,
  .decision-card:focus-visible {
    border-color: var(--text);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .decision-card span {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.76rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    letter-spacing: 0.07em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .decision-card p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .section-heading {
    margin-bottom: 44px;
  }

  .section-heading h2 {
    margin: 0 0 22px;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--secondary);
  }

  .section-heading p {
    margin: 0 0 20px;
    max-width: 38rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .foundation-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 16px;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .foundation-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .foundation-card h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 4px;
    color: var(--title);
  }

  .foundation-card p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .foundation-card ul {
    margin: 12px 0 0;
    padding-left: 18px;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .foundation-card li {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .field-study-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 18px;
    max-width: 68rem;
    margin-bottom: 54px;
  }

  .field-study-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    background: #f8f7f4;
  }

  .field-study-card a {
    display: block;
    color: inherit;
    text-decoration: none;
    height: 100%;
  }

  .field-study-card a:hover h3,
  .field-study-card a:focus-visible h3 {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 0.14em;
  }

  .field-study-card img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
    object-fit: cover;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
  }

  .field-study-content {
    padding: 18px;
  }

  .field-study-content h3 {
    margin: 0 0 10px;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--title);
  }

  .field-study-content p:last-child {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.48;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .secondary-heading {
    margin-top: 8px;
  }

  .field-list,
  .proof-list {
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .field-entry,
  .proof-entry {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 34px 0;
  }

  .field-entry:first-child,
  .proof-entry:first-child {
    border-top: 0;
    padding-top: 0;
  }

  .field-entry h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .field-entry h3 a {
    color: var(--title);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .field-entry h3 a:hover,
  .field-entry h3 a:focus-visible {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 0.14em;
  }

  .field-entry .entry-meta,
  .proof-entry .entry-meta {
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .field-entry p:last-child {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .proof-principle {
    margin: 0 0 10px;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--title);
  }

  .proof-application {
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .supporting-post {
    position: relative;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 24px 20px 20px;
    margin-top: 30px;
  }

  .supporting-post span {
    position: absolute;
    top: -0.42rem;
    left: 18px;
    padding: 0 10px;
    background: #f8f7f4;
    font-size: 0.68rem;
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--secondary);
    font-weight: 400;
    opacity: 0.85;
  }

  .supporting-post h3 {
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .supporting-post h3 a {
    color: var(--title);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .supporting-post h3 a:hover,
  .supporting-post h3 a:focus-visible {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 0.14em;
  }

  .supporting-post p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .learning-close > p {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 0 0 18px;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .learning-close > p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .decision-grid,
    .field-study-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
</Layout>
